Blueprint: Design Using OpenAPI

A blueprint for beginning the API lifecycle by designing a new API using an OpenAPI.

Define

Properly define the API.

  • Team Workspace - A team workspace for managing an API.
  • Team - The team working on an API.
  • Github Repository - A Github repository.
  • Github Repository - A Github repository.
  • Use Cases - The business use cases for an API.

Design

Design the surface of the API.

  • OpenAPI - The OpenAPI specification for an API.
  • Design Patterns - Known API patterns for use in API design.

Mock

Provide a mock for the API.

  • Mock Server - A mocked server for anAPI.
  • Examples - Examples of API request, responses, and messages.

Document

Provide humans with documentation.

  • Reference Documentation - Documentation that describes the entire surface area of an API.
  • Workflow Documentation - Documentation for API workflows.

Test

Ensure an API has proper testing.

  • Contract Testing - The contract test for an API.
  • Performance Testing - Performance testing for an API.
  • Security Testing - The security tests for an API.

Monitor

Monitoring all of the API tests.

  • Contract Monitor - A monitor for an APIs contract test.
  • Performance Monitor - A monitor for the performance testing.
  • Security Monitor - A monitor for the security tests.

Deploy

Deploy an instance of an API.

  • CI/CD Pipeline - The CI/CD pipeline for an API.
  • Gateway - A gateway used to publish an API.

Manage

Manage the access to an API.

  • Onboarding - Where to onboard for an API.
  • Usage Plan - A usage plan for defining access across APIs.
  • Key - An key for accessing an API.

Discover

Ensure an API is discoverable.

  • Private Network - A private network for publishing APIs.
  • Public Network - A public network for publishing APIs.
  • Search - A search for APIs.

Retire

Begin the retirement of an API.

  • Retire - Beginning the process of retiring an API.
  • Deprecate - Shutting down an API, and making it so it can't be used.
  • Archive - Archiving an API so it is available for historic purposes.
